  "prompt": "What were the major events that happened in 2005?",
  "response": "2005 was a year marked by significant global events across politics, natural disasters, science, and culture. Here are some of the major events that occurred:\n\n---\n\n### **Natural Disasters**\n1. **Hurricane Katrina** (August 2005): One of the deadliest and costliest hurricanes in U.S. history, Katrina devastated the Gulf Coast, particularly New Orleans. The storm caused over 1,800 deaths and led to widespread criticism of the government\u2019s response.\n\n2. **Kashmir Earthquake** (October 8, 2005): A 7.6-magnitude earthquake struck the Kashmir region, affecting Pakistan, India, and Afghanistan. Over 80,000 people were killed, and millions were left homeless.\n\n3. **Hurricane Wilma** (October 2005): The most intense Atlantic hurricane on record, Wilma caused significant damage in Mexico, Cuba, and Florida.\n\n---\n\n### **Politics and International Relations**\n1. **Pope John Paul II\u2019s Death and Pope Benedict XVI\u2019s Election** (April 2005): Pope John Paul II passed away on April 2, and Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger was elected as Pope Benedict XVI on April 19.\n\n2. **London Bombings** (July 7, 2005): A series of coordinated terrorist attacks on London\u2019s public transportation system killed 52 people and injured over 700.\n\n3. **Israeli Disengagement from Gaza** (August-September 2005): Israel withdrew its settlements and military from the Gaza Strip, ending a 38-year occupation.\n\n4. **Angela Merkel Becomes Chancellor of Germany** (November 22, 2005): Merkel became the first female Chancellor of Germany, a position she would hold for 16 years.\n\n5. **Iran Nuclear Talks** (2005): Tensions escalated over Iran\u2019s nuclear program, with negotiations and international pressure intensifying.\n\n---\n\n### **Science and Technology**\n1. **YouTube Launched** (February 2005): Founded by Chad Hurley, Steve Chen, and Jawed Karim, YouTube quickly became a major platform for video sharing.\n\n2. **Airbus A380 Maiden Flight** (April 27, 2005): The world\u2019s largest passenger airliner made its first flight, symbolizing advancements in aviation technology.\n\n3. **Deep Impact Mission** (July 4, 2005): NASA\u2019s Deep Impact spacecraft successfully collided with Comet Tempel 1 to study its composition.\n\n---\n\n### **Culture and Entertainment**\n1. **Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince Released** (July 16, 2005): The sixth book in J.K. Rowling\u2019s Harry Potter series broke sales records worldwide.\n\n2. **Live 8 Concerts** (July 2, 2005): A series of global concerts aimed at raising awareness of poverty and debt relief in Africa, coinciding with the G8 Summit.\n\n3. **Brokeback Mountain Released** (December 12, 2005): This critically acclaimed film, directed by Ang Lee, addressed themes of homosexuality and became a cultural milestone.\n\n---\n\n### **Sports**\n1. **Ashes Series** (2005): England regained the Ashes from Australia in one of the most thrilling cricket series in history.\n\n2. **Lance Armstrong\u2019s Tour de France Win**** (July 2005): Armstrong won his seventh consecutive Tour de France, though his victories were later stripped due to doping scandals.\n\n---\n\n### **Other Notable Events**\n1. **Saddam Hussein\u2019s Trial Begins** (October 2005): The former Iraqi dictator faced charges of crimes against humanity.\n\n2. **Measurements of Pluto\u2019s Moons** (2005): Two new moons of Pluto, Nix and Hydra, were discovered by the Hubble Space Telescope.\n\n---\n\nThese events shaped the year 2005, leaving a lasting impact on global history and culture.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
